NASA Space Camp is an educational program that provides hands-on, experiential learning experiences for students and educators. The program focuses on space science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) and aims to inspire interest in these areas, as well as promote teamwork, leadership, and problem-solving skills. The program was founded in 1982 by space industry veteran Dr. Wernher von Braun and is run by the U.S. Space & Rocket Center (USSRC) in Huntsville, Alabama.

Space Camp consists of various activities, workshops, and simulations that allow participants to experience the challenges of working in a space mission. The activities cover topics such as rocket science, astronaut training, robotics, and mission planning, with a focus on using real NASA hardware and facilities. The program is open to students from grades 4 through 12, as well as educators and adults who wish to expand their knowledge of space science. In addition to the residential program at the USSRC, Space Camp also offers virtual camps, educator programs, and teacher workshops.

Space Camp has gained widespread popularity and has grown to include programs in various countries around the world, such as France, Germany, Japan, Brazil, and Australia. It has inspired generations of students to pursue careers in STEM and to take an active interest in space exploration and science. 🙂  :)  :) 🙂  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)  :)   corners (2020)
"Corners" is a 2020 Romanian film directed by Tudor Giurgiu and written by Tudor Giurgiu and Raluca Aprodu. The film follows the story of three siblings who return to their hometown in Transylvania after their mother's death. The siblings are a Romanian-Jewish doctor, a Romanian-Jewish motivational speaker, and a successful businessman living in London. The siblings uncover the details of their family's past and the secrets their parents had kept from them. The film explores themes of family, identity, and the impact of history on the present.

The movie premiered at the 77th Venice Film Festival in September 2020 and received positive reviews from critics for its acting, direction, and emotional depth. The movie was Romania's official submission for the Best International Feature Film category at the 93rd Academy Awards but did not make the final shortlist.

In Part 3 of the exploration of the cosmos, the primary focus shifts towards the study of distant galaxies, stars, and celestial phenomena. Some of the key objectives of Part 3 include:

1. Investigate the formation and evolution of galaxies: Scientists will study the distribution of matter, energy, and structure in galaxies to understand their formation, evolution, and interactions with one another.
2. Discover exoplanets: By analyzing the light from distant stars, astronomers will search for signs of exoplanets, or planets orbiting stars outside our solar system. This research will provide valuable insights into the diversity of planetary systems and the possibility of life beyond Earth.
3. Study quasars: Quasars are extremely energetic, luminous objects in the distant universe that emit large amounts of energy, some of which exceeds the emissions from entire galaxies. The study of quasars will provide valuable insights into the early universe, the structure of black holes, and the nature of the cosmic microwave background radiation.
4. Investigate dark matter and dark energy: Dark matter is a hypothetical form of matter thought to be five times more abundant than ordinary matter, but it does not emit, absorb or reflect light. Its presence can be inferred through its gravitational effects on visible matter. Dark energy is an even more enigmatic phenomenon thought to be responsible for the accelerating expansion of the universe. The search for these mysterious components will help scientists better understand the universe's structure and fate.
5. Study the early universe: By observing the cosmic microwave background radiation, the afterglow of the Big Bang, scientists can study the origins and early evolution of the universe. This research will help scientists understand the physical laws and conditions that governed the universe during its earliest moments.
6. Investigate cosmic ray sources: Cosmic rays are high-energy particles and radiation that originate outside the solar system. By studying their properties, scientists hope to learn about the sources of cosmic rays and their interactions with the medium they travel through.
